  "prompt": "What are some examples of liquids turning to gas?",
  "response": "Here are some common examples of liquids turning into gases, a process known as **vaporization** (which includes evaporation and boiling):\n\n1. **Water Boiling**: When water is heated to its boiling point (100\u00b0C or 212\u00b0F at sea level), it turns into water vapor (steam).\n\n2. **Evaporation of Water**: At temperatures below boiling, water molecules can escape from the surface of the liquid and turn into gas (water vapor), such as when a puddle dries up.\n\n3. **Alcohol Evaporating**: Rubbing alcohol (isopropyl alcohol) evaporates quickly at room temperature, turning into a gas.\n\n4. **Nail Polish Remover (Acetone)**: Acetone, a common ingredient in nail polish remover, evaporates rapidly into a gas at room temperature.\n\n5. **Gasoline Evaporating**: Gasoline, a liquid fuel, evaporates into a gas, which is why it\u2019s important to handle it carefully.\n\n6. **Liquid Nitrogen Boiling**: At room temperature, liquid nitrogen boils and turns into a gas (nitrogen gas) because its boiling point is extremely low (-196\u00b0C or -321\u00b0F).\n\n7. **Perfume Spray**: When perfume is sprayed, the liquid fragrance evaporates into the air as a gas, allowing it to spread and be smelled.\n\n8. **Cooking Oil Heating**: When cooking oil is heated to a high temperature, it begins to break down and release gases, which can be seen as smoke.\n\n9. **Liquid Propane Boiling**: Propane, stored as a liquid under pressure, turns into a gas when released, which is then used for heating or cooking.\n\n10. **Hydraulic Fluid in Extreme Heat**: Under high temperatures, hydraulic fluids can vaporize and turn into gas.\n\nThese processes occur when the liquid absorbs enough energy (usually heat) to overcome the forces holding its molecules together, allowing them to escape into the gaseous state.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
